p: Phytochemical T1, qingdainone, has a binding energy of −9.6 kcal/mol. T1 is a quinazoline alkaloid produced by Strobilanthes cusia, a herb with antiviral activity [ 36]. Figure 5a shows the TMPRSS2 residues that form hydrogen bonds or π-π stacking interactions with T1. TMPRSS2 residue D440 forms C-H⋯O type hydrogen bond with T1 whereas residue A399 forms C-H⋯N type hydrogen bond with T1. Further, T1 forms hydrophobic contacts with residues I381, S382, T387, E388, N398, A400, D440, C465 and A466.
